column2: The Patricia Adams Show & Ray Santisi Trio
column8: The first Sunday of each month, Jazz vocalist, Patricia Adams and the Ray Santisi Trio entertain you with songs from Tin Pan Alley and Harlem renaissance. The band features Berklee College of Music professor and international jazz legend Ray Santisi [piano], Dave Zox [bass], Gary Johnson [drums] and Patricia Adams [vocals].Reviewed by The Boston Globe as "A knockout of a show", people come from as far away as Maine and New York to hear this great music, played in the authentic styles of composers Duke Ellington, Irving Berlin, Cole Porter et. al. For a preview go to www.myspace.com/patriciaadams/radioThe brunch menu offers select specialties of Chef Mitch from Belgium waffles to salmon hash, traditional and creative breakfast and lunch fare. There is something for every palate. Ryles Sunday jazz brunch is a great way to introduce children of all ages to jazz.There is no cover charge. The venue is wheelchair accessible and family friendly. All major credit cards are accepted. Two complimentary parking lots marked S&S.

column4: The Boston Center for the Arts, Cyclorama
column8:
The Ellis Antiques Show ran for 49 years in Boston before closing its doors in 2008. The Boston Antiques Show ran for 21 years, with its final year in 2001. Re- launched in 2011 by Tony Fusco & Robert Four, the new Ellis Boston Antiques Show was a sensational success and the producers are proud to announce The Ellis Boston Antiques Show for October 18-21, 2012.The show features 40 exhibitors of the highest quality, drawn from both past Ellis and Boston Antiques Show exhibitors as well as many new additions offering antiques, fine art, decorative arts, jewelry, silver, quilts, rare maps and prints and more.Once again Boston, a world-class city, has a world-class antiques show and sale.Gala Preview Benefit
The show opens with a Gala Preview on Thursday, October 18 to benefit Ellis Memorial & Eldredge House, Inc., Bostons first settlement house. Located in Bostons South End, Ellis Memorial has been caring for children, disabled adults, and families who live and work in the South End and adjacent neighborhoods since 1885.The Venue - The Cyclorama
The Cyclorama, erected in 1884, is the signature building of the Boston Center for the Arts (BCA), and an ideal venue for this exciting show. It was built to exhibit a huge circular painting - The Battle of Gettysburg - and its circular floorplan encourages visitors to wander the entire show.The Weekend Show and Special Programs
The show is open to the public Friday 1-8, Saturday 11-8 and Sunday 11-5 and we anticipate attendance exceeding 3,000 antique collectors, art buyers and arts patrons. Admission is $15 at the door, with children under 12 free. Admission includes the show catalog, all special programs, and re-admission throughout the weekend. Friday evening from 6pm to 8pm will be "New Collectors Night", featuring programs designed to introduce new collectors to the world of antiques. Additional programs and special offerings are planned for both Saturday and Sunday
